**No — JPQL does NOT automatically return only specific columns based on the projection interface.**  
Spring Data JPA does the projection mapping **AFTER** the query executes, based on **property getters** in your projection interface.

***

# ✅ **What Projections Actually Mean**

Projection means:

> “Return **only the fields I ask for**, instead of the entire entity.”

But **you must request those fields** — Spring does *not* magically trim columns unless you tell it to.

***

# ✅ **Two Types of Projections**

### **1️⃣ Interface‑Based Projections (your example)**

```java
public interface UserNameOnly {
    String getName();
}
```

Repository:

```java
List<UserNameOnly> findByStatus(UserStatus status);
```

👉 For **simple derived queries**, Spring generates a query selecting **all columns**, but returns only the interface fields because projection *reads only the getters*.  
Spring Data’s projection mechanism maps **selected fields to interface getters**, not the whole entity. [\[docs.spring.io\]](https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/commons/docs/1.4.0.M1/reference/html/)

*But note:*  
**Even though the projection exposes only `name`, the SQL may still select the entire row unless you specify a custom JPQL query.**

***

### **2️⃣ JPQL‑Backed Projections (recommended for performance)**

```java
@Query("SELECT u.name AS name FROM User u WHERE u.status = :status")
List<UserNameOnly> findByStatus(@Param("status") UserStatus status);
```

👉 Here JPQL explicitly selects **only `name`**, so only that column is fetched.  
This is a true projection at the database level.

***

# ❗ Key Clarification (Most Important Part)

### ❌ WRONG assumption

> “JPQL returns exact columns automatically based on the class type.”

### ✔ CORRECT behavior

*   **JPQL returns whatever columns YOU SELECT.**
*   **If you do `SELECT u`, it loads the full entity.**
*   **If you do `SELECT u.name`, it loads only that column.**

Spring will then map the results into:

*   Entity (`User`)
*   Interface projection (`UserNameOnly`)
*   DTO projection
*   Record projection

depending on your method return type.  
Spring Data documentation clearly says JPQL queries operate on entities, but projections map selected fields to interface getters. [\[docs.spring.io\]](https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/commons/docs/1.4.0.M1/reference/html/)

***

# 🧠 Mental Model

**Projection ≠ JPQL auto-selecting columns**  
Projection = **Spring mapping only the fields defined in your projection interface**

If you want actual DB‑level column trimming, you must write **explicit JPQL projections**:

```java
SELECT u.name FROM User u
```

***

# 📌 Final Summary for GitHub Notes

*   JPQL does **not** auto-select only projection columns
*   To fetch specific columns, write **explicit JPQL SELECT**
*   Interface projections map getter names → selected columns
*   Derived queries still select full entity row unless customized

